    <!-- ─── How It\'s Made Screen ─── -->
    <string name="how_its_made">How It\'s Made</string>
    <string name="hale_wood_process">The Hale Wood Process</string>
    <string name="hale_wood_desc">Discover the traditional 5-step process of crafting authentic Channapatna toys using natural Hale wood and vegetable dyes.</string>
    <string name="step_1_title">Selecting Hale Wood</string>
    <string name="step_1_desc">Artisans harvest Hale wood (Wrightia tinctoria), known for its soft texture and safe properties. The wood is seasoned for months to remove moisture.</string>
    <string name="step_2_title">Turning on the Lathe</string>
    <string name="step_2_desc">The seasoned wood is cut into manageable pieces and shaped on a lathe. Artisans use hand-held chisels to carve intricate designs while the wood spins rapidly.</string>
    <string name="step_3_title">Applying Natural Lac</string>
    <string name="step_3_desc">A stick of colored lac is pressed against the spinning wood. The friction melts the lac, creating a vibrant, non-toxic, and uniform coating.</string>
    <string name="step_4_title">Polishing with Palm Leaves</string>
    <string name="step_4_desc">To achieve the signature glossy finish, artisans press dried screw pine (Mogali) leaves against the spinning toy. This natural polishing technique gives the toy its radiant shine.</string>
    <string name="step_5_title">Assembly and Finishing</string>
    <string name="step_5_desc">The individual lacquered parts are carefully assembled. Any final details are added, resulting in a beautiful, safe, and heritage-rich wooden toy.</string>

